===============================================================================================================================
❌ Problem in the Original Code
Your original function:
void *add2nums(uint8_t a,uint8_t b){
    uin8_t sum = 0;
    sum = a+b;
    return &sum;
}

❗ Big mistake:

You are returning the address of a local variable (sum).

What happens?

sum is created inside the function → stored in the stack frame of the function.

When the function returns → stack frame is destroyed → sum no longer exists.

So you return a dangling pointer → pointing to memory that is invalid.

This is undefined behavior.

Sometimes:

It prints garbage value

It crashes

It may even appear to work (but it's still wrong)

✔ Why Your Second Code Works

You changed:

uint16_t sum = 0;   // global variable


Now sum is global, stored in data segment, not on the stack.

Global variable lifetime = entire program.
So returning its address is valid.

🧠 Memory Explanation (Interview-Level)
❌ Case 1: Local variable
add2nums() stack frame:
+------------+
| sum = 220  |
+------------+

return &sum  ---> INVALID after function ends


After function returns:

Stack memory reused → sum disappears

✔ Case 2: Global variable
.data section:
+-----------------+
| sum (lives forever) |
+-----------------+


This memory never gets deleted, so returning &sum is safe.

⚠ But interviewer will still ask:

Is the second solution correct in general?

Correct answer:

It works, but it is not good practice because:

❌ Problems:

Function is not re-entrant

If called from interrupt + main → race condition

Only one sum value can be stored

Multiple calls overwrite the same variable

Not thread-safe

⭐ Best Professional Embedded C Solution (Recommended)
Return by value (simple and safe):
uint16_t add2nums(uint8_t a, uint8_t b){
    return (uint16_t)(a + b);
}

int main(){
    uint16_t result = add2nums(100,120);
    printf("%u\n", result);
}


✔ Stack-safe
✔ Re-entrant
✔ No global variables
✔ No pointer issues
✔ No dynamic memory needed

⭐ Alternative Embedded-Style (Return result using pointer)
void add2nums(uint8_t a, uint8_t b, uint16_t *out)
{
    *out = a + b;
}

int main(void){
    uint16_t sum;
    add2nums(100,120, &sum);
    printf("%u\n", sum);
}


This method is very common in drivers and HAL code.
